Feature: Delivery Endpoint

    The Delivery Endpoint feature enables the recording of product deliveries from external suppliers into the network. This process is critical for integrating inbound inventory into the system, maintaining accurate stock levels, and ensuring efficient supply chain operations. Deliveries are thoroughly documented to provide real-time updates and complete traceability of incoming stock.

    The objective of this feature is to provide a standardised method for logging and managing deliveries from external sources. By capturing essential details such as supplier information, delivery quantities, and timestamps, the Delivery Endpoint supports effective inventory management and supplier performance monitoring.

    The Delivery Endpoint feature ensures that:

    * Incoming stock is recorded and updated in real time across the system.
    * Deliveries are accurately documented with all relevant details.
    * Businesses maintain visibility and control over inventory integration from external suppliers.

    === Reasons for External Deliveries

    External deliveries occur due to various operational, logistical, and strategic needs. The table below highlights the most common scenarios:

    [cols="3,7", options="header"]
    |===
    | Reason Category           | Specific Reasons
    | Supply Chain Operations   a| * Supplier Fulfilment: Receiving stock ordered from external suppliers.
    * Emergency Procurement: Addressing unexpected demand surges or stockouts.
    * Seasonal Stock: Acquiring additional inventory for seasonal demand.
    | Inventory Restocking       a| * Regular Restocking: Replenishing stock levels to meet operational needs.
    * Bulk Procurement: Acquiring large quantities of goods to optimise costs.
    | Quality and Compliance     a| * Quality Replacement: Receiving replacement stock for defective or returned goods.
    * Regulatory Supply: Fulfilling inventory needs tied to compliance requirements.
    |===

    === Key Elements of Delivery

    Deliveries are recorded with the following essential details:

    * *Quantity delivered*: The exact number of items received.
    * *Supplier details*: Information about the supplier providing the goods.
    * *Delivery date and time*: When the stock was received.
    * *Delivery reference*: Unique identifier or reference for the delivery.
    * *Receiving location*: The location where the stock is integrated into the network.

    === Purpose

    The Delivery Endpoint supports the following objectives:

    * Ensuring accurate and timely updates of inventory from external suppliers.
    * Maintaining visibility and traceability of incoming stock across the network.
    * Enhancing operational efficiency and supplier relationship management through precise tracking and documentation of deliveries.

    This functionality empowers organisations to streamline inventory integration, reduce errors, and maintain consistency in supply chain processes.

